{"source_key":"sha256-4f3dcaa24e6b216c81e2c792e5295e32","record_index":262,"record_hash":"sha256:9836e7cdc6d1716cc68d0c099430d2196295ce7cc4862c673f3fc892d6535c4c","timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:41:57.515Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: c90ab7\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2345\nOutput:\nFor public v1, the Forge server should be able to create an Agent Trail snapshot\non demand by fetching GitMeta metadata for the repository referenced by the PR\nURL.\n\nExample local setup:\n\n```ini\n[remote \"meta\"]\n  url = git@github.com:gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\n  fetch = +refs/meta/main:refs/meta/remote/main\n  meta = true\n  promisor = true\n  partialclonefilter = blob:none\n```\n\nThe server should not assume it can see a developer's local Git remote config.\nGiven a URL like:\n\n```text\nhttps://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler/pull/13936\n```\n\nthe server should resolve the public GitHub repository, then try to fetch the\nmetadata refs from the public repository or a configured metadata remote.\n\nPossible first flow:\n\n1. parse the PR URL into forge, owner, repo, and PR number\n2. check that the repository and pull request are public/readable\n3. create or refresh a server-side bare/cache checkout for the repository\n4. try to fetch `refs/meta/main`\n5. if metadata is available, run `but-agentlog` lookup/projection code against\n   the fetched repository metadata\n6. generate a review-safe Agent Trail snapshot\n7. cache or return that snapshot according to the retention policy\n\nThe server can lazy-initialize repository storage. On the first request for a\nrepository, clone or otherwise create a bare/cache checkout. On later requests,\nreuse the cached repository and fetch updates, especially metadata refs, instead\nof recloning.\n\nAfter a repository has been initialized once, normal Agent Trail lookup should\nbe:\n\n```text\nrefresh cached repo -> fetch metadata refs -> query sessions for PR/branch/change\n```\n\nFollow-up checks for the same repository should not need another clone. They\nshould re-fetch before looking for metadata, then run the relevant\n`but-agentlog` lookup for the pull request, branch, review, or change target.\n\nThe first clone/fetch should be treated as part of on-demand page generation.\nThe UI can show a loadi\n[TRUNCATED]\nr commit evidence, if added\n\nWeak signals:\n\n- backfilled turns with only capture-time environment snapshots\n- broad sessions that span unrelated work\n- sidecar review sessions that discuss the branch but did not implement it\n- turns related only through current branch state\n\nThe UI should expose why a turn is highlighted. Reviewers should not have to\nguess why a session appears.\n\n## Privacy And Publication\n\nAgent Trail is more sensitive than local handoff because it is meant to be\nopened by colleagues.\n\nBefore publishing or linking:\n\n- records must be redacted\n- local filesystem paths should not be exposed\n- raw provider session ids should not be exposed\n- hidden/system/developer prompts should not be exposed\n- source records should stay bounded and redacted\n- the user should understand that the trail may contain prompts and tool output\n\nThe first product design needs an explicit publication boundary. Capturing data\ninto GitMeta does not automatically mean every pull request should expose a\npublic or team-visible Agent Trail.\n\n## Permissions\n\nFirst version: public repositories and public metadata only.\n\nThe server may generate or show an Agent Trail only when it can access the PR\nand GitMeta metadata without private credentials. Private repository support\nshould be a later design pass.\n\nFuture policy options:\n\n- GitButler team/workspace members\n- same users who can view the repository\n- same users who can view the pull request\n- explicit share link recipients\n\nFor private repositories, defaulting to repository/PR visibility is probably the\nleast surprising, but do not build that into v1.\n\n## Non-Goals\n\n- no claim that agent sessions authored the pull request\n- no full transcript dump as the main experience\n- no copying transcript records onto pull request targets\n- no product-specific review payloads inside `but-agentlog`\n- no magic generated summary as the source of truth\n- no automatic public publishing just because capture succeeded\n- no cryptographic audit or compliance story for v1\n\n## Open Questions\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:41:57.515Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}